## Why we need this now

Two industry signals make this moment unusually important.

First, major labs and ecosystem leaders are converging on the idea that **memory and infrastructure are becoming core differentiators**, not side features. Google’s Titans work explicitly proposes a neural long-term memory module that learns to memorize historical context, while NVIDIA is increasingly positioning itself as a provider of the full AI infrastructure stack above and below models. :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}

Second, the market direction is shifting from “sell software” toward “sell intelligence as a utility.” Sam Altman recently described a future where intelligence is sold “like electricity or water,” metered by usage; separately, a widely circulated but not yet cleanly primary-sourced quote has him saying he bets there is another major post-Transformer architecture still to be found. The first claim is well reported; the second should be treated as **emerging / secondary-source only**. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

**Interpretation:** if intelligence becomes abundant and metered, then durable advantage shifts toward what makes intelligence *persistent, personalized, governable, and compounding*. That points directly at memory. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

