## Why start with episodic memory first

### Core idea in simple words

Before an agent can remember **how to do something well**, it must remember **what actually happened**.

A novel procedural memory that is not grounded in good episodes risks becoming:
- brittle
- stale
- reward-hacked
- over-generalized
- unsafe to reuse

This is why our order is:

```text
EPISODES → PROCEDURES → CONSOLIDATION → INTENTIONS
```

### Why this appeared historically

The best-known early memory systems all expose the same pattern:

- **Generative Agents** stored experiences and reflected over them. :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}
- **Reflexion** improved behavior using feedback from prior attempts. :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}
- **Voyager** turned successful behavior into a reusable skill library. :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}
- **MemRL** pushes this further by learning utility over episodic memory, not just semantic similarity. :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}

### Practical interpretation

A novel procedural memory should not be hand-authored first and justified later.  
It should be **earned from validated episodic traces**.

