## How we differ from the 7 emerging memory architectures

Below is a synthesis, not a dismissal. Each of these papers or systems contributes something important.

### 1. Agentic Memory (AgeMem)
AgeMem integrates short-term and long-term memory management directly into the policy and exposes memory operations as tool actions. Strong idea: **the agent learns memory operations**. Our difference is that we are prioritizing **procedural memory formation from grounded episodes** and a future consolidation path, not only unified memory control. :contentReference[oaicite:15]{index=15}

### 2. Memex
Memex focuses on indexed experience memory that compresses long-horizon context without discarding evidence. Strong idea: **keep evidence while compressing context**. Our difference is that we are targeting a fuller ladder from episode → procedure → consolidation → intention, not only experience indexing. :contentReference[oaicite:16]{index=16}

### 3. MemRL
MemRL is one of the most relevant comparators because it learns utility over episodic memory through runtime reinforcement learning. Strong idea: **not all memories are equally valuable**. Our difference is that we want to turn high-value episodes into **validated procedural memory objects**, then later consolidate them into a future-facing system. :contentReference[oaicite:17]{index=17}

### 4. UMA (Unified Memory Agent)
The emerging survey literature uses “unified” memory framing to pull together forms, functions, and dynamics across agent systems. Strong idea: **memory should be treated as a system, not a feature**. Our difference is a stronger product thesis around **procedural memory first as the durable compounding layer**, grounded by episodes and built for prospective extension. :contentReference[oaicite:18]{index=18}

### 5. Pancake
Pancake frames memory as a hierarchical serving problem for multi-agent systems, with caching and GPU/CPU coordination. Strong idea: **memory is also a systems and serving problem**. Our difference is that we are not only optimizing memory as infrastructure; we are designing memory as **behavioral capital** that later drives procedures and intentions. :contentReference[oaicite:19]{index=19}

### 6. Conditional Memory
Conditional Memory introduces scalable lookup as a new sparsity axis for LLMs. Strong idea: **memory can be conditional and selective at model/runtime level**. Our difference is that we are focused on **agent memory objects with provenance, validation, governance, and promotion**, not only conditional lookup mechanics. :contentReference[oaicite:20]{index=20}

### 7. Multi-Agent Memory from a Computer Architecture Perspective
This line of work reframes multi-agent memory as hierarchy, cache sharing, consistency, and access control. Strong idea: **memory becomes a distributed systems problem at scale**. Our difference is that our near-term build order is centered on the single-agent memory ladder first, while keeping future compatibility with multi-agent consistency and shared-memory protocols. :contentReference[oaicite:21]{index=21}

