## Who really needs this

### Personal AI
A personal AI needs durable continuity, preferences, repeated routines, and future follow-through. Altman has publicly described a direction where AI becomes deeply personal and increasingly utility-like. That makes memory central, not optional. :contentReference[oaicite:22]{index=22}

### Wearables
Wearables create high-frequency, real-world, time-sequenced data. That is exactly where episodic traces, intention systems, and safe personalization matter most.

### Robotics
Robots need remembered episodes, skill reuse, and future-task commitments under physical constraints. Google’s Titans and broader world-model / long-term memory work point to growing pressure for architectures that can preserve useful history over long horizons. :contentReference[oaicite:23]{index=23}

### Research agents
Karpathy’s `autoresearch` is a strong signal for this direction: repeated experiments, measurable outcomes, and looped improvement. That environment is almost tailor-made for episode → procedure → consolidation pipelines. :contentReference[oaicite:24]{index=24}

### AI Operating Systems
If AI operating systems become real, memory will be one of their most important internal services: state, retrieval, skill reuse, preferences, scheduling, and permissions. MemGPT already framed part of this future through tiered memory management. :contentReference[oaicite:25]{index=25}

### Enterprise AI
support ops, sales ops, procurement, compliance, internal copilots, DevOps runbooks
